<section xml:id="ref.data.mutable">
<title>Mutable State</title>

<para>A <firstterm>mutable object</firstterm> is value on which <ind>operations</ind> may
yield different results when called at different times.
Mutable objects are common in imperative programming languages.
They reflect the concept of a <ind>storage location</ind> in a von Neumann-style architecture.  
Most of Orc's value types are <ind>immutable</ind>.</para>

<para>Orc provides the following standard mutable value types:
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para><code><ind>Ref</ind></code>: Reference to a value that can be changed</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><ind>Cell</ind></code>: A write-once <code>Ref</code></para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><ind>Buffer</ind></code>: A queue of values</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><ind>BoundedBuffer</ind></code>: A queue of values with a maximum size</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><ind>Array</ind></code>: A mutable integer-indexed sequence of values</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><ind>Set</ind></code>: A mutable set of values</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><ind>Counter</ind></code>: A value that can be incremented and decremented atomically</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><ind>Dictionary</ind></code>: A mutable <ind>Record</ind></para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>
See the <olink targetdoc="ref.stdlib.state">state library</olink> section for more details on the value types.
</para>


